While the scout runs, I realized a **much cleaner route for the odd/unramified case** than what I wrote on the board: for odd-order `H`, you don't need Schur–Zassenhaus on an extension group or a Maschke embedding at all — you just **average the bilinear form**. Given any bilinear refinement `f₀` of `q` (with `f₀ v v = q v`), set `f(v,w) := ∑_{h∈H} f₀(h•v, h•w)`. Then:
- `f v v = ∑_h q(h•v) = ∑_h q(v) = |H|·q(v) = q(v)` since `|H|` is odd (`=1` in `ZMod 2`);
- `f` is `H`-invariant by reindexing `h ↦ hg`;

so `m = 0` works via the already-proved `isEquivariantFactorSet_of_biadditive_invariant`. The whole odd case collapses to one reusable sub-lemma: **a bilinear refinement `f₀` of a char-2 quadratic form exists** (the only part needing a basis). Let me record this plan.
